    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1975-01-23T10:18:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1975-01-23T09:35:00-05:00" n="354"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d354">
                <head>354. Memorandum of Conversation<note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d354fn1"
                        >Source: Ford Library, National Security Adviser, Memoranda of Conversation,
                        Box 8. Secret; <gloss target="#t_Nodis1">Nodis</gloss>. The meeting took
                        place in the Oval Office.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            from="1975-01-23T09:35:00-05:00" to="1975-01-23T10:18:00-05:00"
                            type="conversation-or-meeting-date">January 23, 1975, 9:35–10:18
                            a.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="participants">
                    <head>PARTICIPANTS</head>
                    <item>President <persName corresp="#p_FGR1">Ford</persName>
                    </item>
                    <item>Dr. <persName corresp="#p_KHA1">Henry A. Kissinger</persName>, Secretary
                        of State and Assistant to the President for National Security Affairs</item>
                    <item>Lt. General <persName corresp="#p_SB3">Brent Scowcroft</persName>, Deputy
                        Assistant to the President for National Security Affairs</item>
                </list>
                <p>[Omitted here is discussion of matters other than the European security
                    conference or <gloss target="#t_MBFR1">MBFR</gloss>.]</p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_KHA1">Kissinger</persName>: On the <gloss target="#t_NSC1"
                        >NSC</gloss> meeting on <gloss target="#t_MBFR1">MBFR</gloss>, the only
                    issue is when to play the nuclear option—all at once or piddling it out.</p>
                <p>The President: Timewise, when should we move?</p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_KHA1">Kissinger</persName>: I wouldn’t decide it at the
                    meeting—just to preserve some flexibility. I would tell <persName
                        corresp="#p_RSR1">Resor</persName> he could give it to <gloss
                        target="#t_NATO1">NATO</gloss> in February and present it at Geneva in
                    March.</p>
                <p>The President: Is there a chance we could have something by the summit?</p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_KHA1">Kissinger</persName>: If there is, it won’t happen
                    at Geneva. If we were willing to agree to equal cuts, we could get one.</p>
                <p>The President: It would help with the Congress.</p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_KHA1">Kissinger</persName>: Our original proposal was
                    ridiculous. The problem with cuts is that it indirectly introduces a ceiling.
                    That is significant to the Soviets.</p>
                <p>If we get serious about <gloss target="#t_MBFR1">MBFR</gloss>, we should do it
                    like <gloss target="#t_SALT1">SALT</gloss>—give them proposals through your
                    channel before surfacing them.</p>
                <p>The President: <persName corresp="#p_SJR1">Schlesinger</persName> isn’t a problem
                    on this, is he?</p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_KHA1">Kissinger</persName>: Not at all. [<hi rend="italic"
                        >2 lines not declassified</hi>]</p>
            </div>
